                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d686">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/1992B</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-07-19T15:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 19, 1915, 3 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1968. Your 2586, July 15, 7 p. m.<note n="1" xml:id="d686fn1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_474">p. 474</ref>.</note> Have
                    indicated to you unwillingness of this Government to enter into any <hi
                        rend="italic">modus vivendi</hi>. It is entirely a question of principle
                    which does not admit of compromise, since that would affect the freedom of
                    American citizens to traverse the high seas to which they are entitled as a
                    matter of right. In your conversations with Foreign Office avoid giving hope
                    that your Government might consider any form of compromise.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
